{"/service/ndnp/kyu/batch_kyu_elkhound_ver01/data/sn86069242/00516998416/1927050501/0721.xml":{"full_text":"THURSDAY MAY 5 1927\nTHE ANDERSON NKWsn\nPAGE THREE\nForeign Trade Opportunities\nFor Young Men and Investors\nBy ROGER W BABSON\nBABSON BARK FLA April 27--Tloger\nW Bulison continues todny a\ndlscHSKlon of his topic \u201cYour Boy\u2019s\nBusiness\u201d with special reference to\nopportunities in shipping anil foreign\ntrade Mr Bn e son believes this is a\ngood field for young men with energy\nand willingness to make sacrifices but\nthat it is a very competitive field\nSays he:\nOne Hundred Years Age\nOne hundred years ago shipping of\nfered the very best opportunities for\nambitious young men Several of my\nancestors of Gloucester Massachusetts\nwent to sea when fourteen years of\nage and worked up to be master of\ntheir ships They sailed these ships to\nAsia Africa and the South Sea Is\nlands taking loads of textiles hard\nware and other New England products\nand trading them for tea pepper\nspices etc This was a wonderful\ntraining for yonng men as these trips\ndeveloped courage initiative and judg\nment as well as integrity industry\nHand knowledge The modern youth\nwould think it a great hardship to\n\"ravel even for one night in one of\nthese sailing vessels to say nothing of\nbeing out six months or a year\nI don\u2019t know what would happen\nunder such conditions to the modern\nsalesman who thinks he must trnvel in\na Pullman cur nnd have n private bn'h\nwhen stopping at a hotel! Yet it was\nthe courage industry nnd thrift of\ntheir ancestors who traveled in sail\nIng ships that provided the money\nwhich later built America\u2019s transcon\ntinentnl railroads and the best hotels\nIn her western cities Yes that was\ngreat training both for business and\nlife It was a trnining which devel\noped the good habits which young men\ntoduy so severely lack Frankly our\ncolleges will never succeed in training\nfor business until they discover some\nway of today accomplishing what\n\u201cgoing to sea\" nnd the \"apprentice\nsystem\u201d accomplished years ago\nKnowledge always can be purchased\nbut good business habits can only be\nacquired through experience\nPresent Day Conditions\nConditions in shipping nnd foreign\ntrade are now infinitely better than\nthey were one hundred years ngo Fine\nsteamers take the place of sailing ships\nthe United States now has consuls at\nevery foreign srt of any consequence\nwhen ashore it is always possible to\nget a clean room nnd fair food while\none\u2019s life when in a foreign lnnd is in\nwho such danger as it was formerly\n\u201cYet\u2014 compared with a good job at\nhome ashore the best job aboard ship\nor in a foreign land is much more\nstrenuous and difficult To begin with\nthe temptations of such n life are fa\ngreater than with a life at home\nHence to succeed in the merchnnt mu\nrine or in foreign lands n young man\nmust be temperate clean and upright\nMost of the men whom I know to have\nsucceeded in such work had moral and\nphysical stamina Of course thou\nsands of Americans are in this work\nwho both drink nnd run around but\ntbev are not the ones who succeed\nMoreover they harm the reputation of\nthe entire country liecause we really\nare judged abroad by the character of\nthose we send abroad\nMany feel that to succeed in ship\nping or foreign trade much entertain\ning is necessary It is true that the\n\u201cnon-mixer\u201d is often lmnrttcnpped in\ndealing with Latin Americans nnd cer\ntain others who demand much atten\ntion before doing business But a\nman may Ik a good mixer nnd yet no\ntouch liquor or be promiscuous One of\nthe best entertainers in the United\nStates\u2014 a man who lias built the elec\ntric water or gas plants in several of\nthe large South American cities\u2014 is a\nteetotaler He buys or rents a line\nhome in the foreign city in which he\nis to operate taking there his wife and\nservants and entertains royally His\nentertaining however is n credit to\nhis country and it never becomes the\ncheap stuff which some of our recent\ncollege graduates think is necessary\nIn order to sell goods to the Latin\nAmericans Hence the first require\nments for success in foreign trade are\nintegrity temperance self-control and\na desire to be of real service Beal\nfriendship is developed by helping\nothers rnther than by mere entertain\nment Where Beat Opportunities Exist\nCorporations nnd individuals con\ntemplating entering foreign trade\nshould most carefully consider the mW\nB vantages nnd disadvantages connected\nvwith the different foreign countries\nForeign trade resembles mining or\ndrilling for ore in that it is very easy\nto lose money in seeking foreign trnde\nunless conditions are Just right For\ninstance probably the greatest foreign\nspeculative possibilities today are in\nconnection with llnssian trade: but\nthese are not for Americans When\nthe time comes to gather the Russian\nharvest it will be gathered by Ger\nmans and not Jiv Amerienns Our only\nmcbance to make money In Russia Is br\nbacking some honest Germans nnd di\nviding with them the pronts Our\nchances to do business In South Amer\nica are much greater than before the\nwar owing to the lnrge sums which we\nrecently have loaned certain South\nAmerican cities and nntions Yet it\nmust Ik remembered thnt the British\nare very firmly entrenched in Soiita\nAmerica and that both the French and\nthe Germans are also keen competitors\nof ours Our tariff protects American\nmanufacturers against competition\nfrom foreign manufacturers in connec\ntion with goods sold In this country\nbut not in connection with goods sold\nabroad When selling abroad only\nservice quality nnd price count\nUntil the recent revolution in Chinn\nstatistics indicated that China offered\n0 the best field for American soldiers of\nfortune Chinn has always felt\nfriendly toward this country and we\nhave always had our full share of her\nbusiness Todny however conditions\nf in China nre fnr worse than in Mexico\nAlmost no government exists in China\ntoday The strongest general is the\ngovernor of n section until he Is con\nquered by another Goods money nnd\nmen are subject to seizure and no re-1\ndress is possible Notwithstanding th\nchaotic conditions I believe that the\norient offers the greatest foreign trnde\nopportunities to Americans for the long\npull Hence were I going into foreign\ntrade I should move to the Pacific\nCoast and make my headquerters in\nSan Francisco or Beattie or some other\ngrowing Pacific port Otherwise 1\nshould select New York or New Or\nleans Hence the first step is to se\nlect the country with which you plan\nto trade and then make your head\nquarters in the city which has \u2019the bent\ntrade routes to said country\nthough we do not now need the help\nof Europe China or Latin America we\nsome day will lie very glad of their\ntrade Hence let us now encourage\nthese corporations Investors and such\nyoung men as are now interested in\nshipping foreign trnde nnd other con\nstructive international work\nThirty-Nine Years Ago\nIsuue of May 3 1888\nMrs M F Hull who on her return\nfrom her purchnslng trip last wees\nwns taken severely ill having conges\ntive chills has recovered sufficiently\nto open her new spring stock of milli\nnery Though delayed by illness and\nsomewhat pressed for time Mrs Hull\nmanaged by the aid of her experienced\nhelp to make a most attractive dis\nplay Saturday More new goods have\nsince come in and her lady friends are\ninvited to call nnd examine\n\u201cPhilosophy of Wit\" is thesubjert of\nEli Perkins' lecture to lie delivered\nhere on Wednesday evening May the\nOth Mr Perkins is conceded to be\none of the finest lecturers in the United\nStates nnd our citizens should not fail\nto hear him\nAt most of the places where tin\nrailroad crosses the pikes or sreets the\ncrossings for vehicles are very insuffi\nciently made Though planks have\nboon put down a cart load of rock for\nfilling in is used where there ought\nto be at least a carload nnd getting\nover it with a buggy is not only mi\npleasant but dangerous Between de\npending on a \"soulless corporation\" b\nmake these crossings and on Col Hanks\nto keep tin rest of the pike in a de\ncent condition the traveling public\nare in the middle of a very bnd fix\nbetween the devil nnd the deep blue\nsea as it were\nAt a Republican mass convention\nheld at the Court House in Lttwrenoo\nImrg Ky for the purpose of sending\ndelegates to the Republican State Con\nvention at Louisville May 2 1SSS\nJames Wash was elected chairman\nand E W Ilraffen wns elected secre\ntary On motion tin following com\nmittee on resolutions were appointed:\n1 S Searcy W II Bell Rufus Searcy\nJim Strndford and T 1 Ballard The\nfollowing named gentlemen are sent\nas delegates to the Louisville conven\ntion: Lnwrenooburg District James\nWash W B Snffell J S Searcy Josh\nMount joy John Strndford Ezra Mc\nGinnis and Henry Bell: Alton District\nJames Hawkins and E W Drnffen:\nTORACCO GROWERS\nSHOULD CONSIDER\nQUALITY RETURNS\nBrat Leaf Can Be Produced Only\nIfu-ough Giving Time to Plant\nBed Getting Good Stand\nThereby Saving\nPROFIT VERSUS L088\nShipping as a Business\nCorporations owned in the United\nStates did not do much in snipping\nduring the generation preceding the\nWorld War Hence when this war\ncame those few corporations and indi\nviduals which owned either smpyards\nor ships became very prosperous As\nis always true these great profits re\nsulted in over-production so that when\nthe war was over there was a surplus\nof ships This resulted in cuttlug\nrates and in general disorganization\nGradually the situation has improved\nFew new ships have been built many\nhave been scrapped while new trade\nroutes have been developed For tin\nfirst time since the Armistice arc the\nshipping interests hopeful Once again\nsome of the best ships on the ocean fly\nthe stnrs and stripes If our Govern\nment at Washington is wise enough\nto keep our merchnnt marine and nut\nlet it lie stolen nwny from us shipping\nwill come hack as an American in\ndustry The only stumbling block nt\nthe moment is the attitude of certain\nlabor leaders and unreasonable petit i\ncinns Labor' legislation by the United\nStates alone is as useless in online -lion\nwith foreign trnde as is tariff leg\nislation For either to do any good\nit must be done internationally and ap\nplicable to all nations However this\nis too large a question to discuss here\nA good illustration of wlmt 1ms\ntaken place in connection with th's\nsince 1!M4 is shown by the quotations\non Atlantic Gulf and West Indies\nS S Co Common Stock This was\nsoiling nt 7 in June in 1014 when Ger\nmany declared war After the war it\nrose to a price of 102 and then grad\nually fell to a low of 04 Todny it is j Palmer District W E Petty and\nselling around 30 All shipping stocks Rufus Senrcy: Chesher District\nhave not had such gyrations but on Bruner Case and Areliy Tinsley Good\nthe other hand some have gone to! night District\u2014 Wade II Morgan and\nnothing and have been willed out on- j Ben Franklin\nlively Because of this severe re-ail- Mrs F Knvniiiiugh Mrs J S\njust mi'll t shipping securities should lie j Lyons and Mrs Lilian! spent\nattractive speculations when the next several days of last week in Louisvill\nbuying zone comes The same tiling\nis Irue regarding the stocks of cer\ntain companies organized during th\nwar to carry on foreign trade Th:\nAmerican Interuiitioiinl Corporation is\nan example of such Its common stock\nwas sold during the war at par: \u2018I\nrose to 122 then declined to 10 and is\nnow selling around 40 Other stocks\nworthy of study by those interested\nin shipping and foreign Irnde are In\nternational Mercantile Marine Ameri\ncan Ship and Commerce Bethlehem\nSteel and Electric Boat\nGeneral Business Outlook\nShipping nnd foreign trnde is closely\nrelated to the general business situa\ntion Yet often during a lK-rioil of\nbusiness depression in the United\nStntes these employed in foreign trade\nhave done their best business This\nlias been due to the fact that at sm li\ntimes manufacturers wore unable to\nsell their output here at home and\nhence were forced to find foreign iinii\nkets The corporations nnd individtiirs\nwho nre trained to put these Ameri\ncan manufacturers in touch with tlicsi\nforeign market reaped a hands uu\nreward Today we arc facing a period\nwhen production will exceed consump\ntion Mills can continue operations\nand liilxir remain employed only as\nwe are aide to sell our surplus gcMids\nabroad This means that our manu\nfacturers will s Min Ik compelled to de\nvelop foreign markets Then once more\nthorn who nre now training to sell\nabroad will hnvc a real opportunity\nIn view of them probable conditions\nIt Is very necessary for ns to get an\ninternational mind nnd see tin world\nns a unit Bo long ns the United\nStates remains selfish nnd conceited\nit will never succeed in developing\nmuch foreign trnde If personal\nfriendship is nil iniiirtnnt facto\nenabling an American salesman to sell\nin a foreign country surely national\nfriendship is even more important\nBusiness still reinnlus guts! nnd the\nBalisonehnrt continues to register\naround 12 per cent above normal Al\nin emphasizing the importance of\nquality and price in determining the\nprofitableness of tobacco the expe\nriences of two growers are cited in\n\u201cControl of Farm Expenses\u201d a new\ncircular published by the Kentuekv\nCollege of Agriculture\nOne mnn operating a 100-acre farm\nplanted 5 acres of tobacco on laud in\nprime condition Having only a mod\nerate acreage to set this mnn was\nable to give good care to the plant tied\nHe produced an abundance of vigor\nous early plants and secured a good\nstand thus saving the expense of u\nlarge amount of resetting The early\nsotting also was conducive to the pro\nduction of a bright leaf of fine tex\nture nnd in highest demand on the\nmarket\nThe crop yielded 1(100 pounds per\nacre and sold for an average of 25\ncents a pound Labor costs were kept 1\ndown since the grower used his own j\nlabor supplemented with a small\namount of hired help The cost per j\nacre was approximately $250 nnd tin\ncrop brought about $400 leaving a net\nprofit of $750 for the five acres in-\neluding compensation for the owner\u2019s\nwork and land at current rates\nAnother grower planted 20 acres to\ntobacco on a 200-acre farm A consid\nerable part of the acreage planted was\nindifferent tobacco land Because the\nacreage undertaken wus too large for\nthe available labor sufficient care\ncould not be given to the tobacco The\nplants were late resulting in a poor\nstand a large expense for resetting\nand an uneven crop maturing into anJ\nof inferior color and quality and low\nyield Tlie crop brought 12 cents a\npound or $85 an acre The cost of\nproduction was excessive liecause of\nilu large amount of high-priced labor\nused The total cost was $2(M an aero\nresulting in a loss of $205 an acre or\nmore Mian $4000 for the entire crop\nTemptation\nWife: Here's a story of a man in\nArabia who sold his wife for a horse\nYou wouldn't sell me for a horse\nwould you darling?\nHuiiliy: Of course not dear! But\nI'd hate to have anyone tempt me with\na really good car\nCREAM WANTED\nI\u2014 lirlHa Kjri\nNtvll\nlS7 VkxtT Mar $917\nU 7 ff\nMu IMM aa Caaa Day (Na\nOnyVtn AUum Sanitary Milk Co\nIsingsriMI\nStation SSPS Broad-\nCasting -Please Stand By\nThe United Stales Government ad\nvises iis to store our Winter Garments\nin Air-Tight Containers\nOUR CLEANING\nKills All Moth Eggs\nWe return the garments to you in\npaper bags you seal the bags and have\nno fear of moths\nINFORMATION ON REQUEST\nWesley Sutherland\nClimb Phone No 6\nLawrenreburg Kentucky\nOOOOOOOOOOOOOOQOOQOb\nA $5000000000\nLoss Is No Joke!\nAccidents are costing the United States five\nbillions each year with 85000 killed\nand 7000000 injured\nThe U 8 F A G Accident Policy is a vital need for every wage earner\nIt Costa Little To Have This Protection!\nNothing To Ask About Itl\nCrain\nRepresenting\nUNITED STATES FIDELITY AND GUARANTY COMPANY\nA Word With\nthe Old Folks\nElderly People Are Learning Importance\nof Qood Elimination\nIN the later years of life there is i\napt to be a slowing up of the\nbodily functions Good elimination\nhowever is just as essential to the\nold as to the young Many old folks\nhave learned the value of Doan\u2019s\nPills when a stimulant diuretic to\nthe kidneys is required Scanty or\nburning passages of kidney secre\ntions are often signs of improper kid\nney function In most every com\nmunity are scores of users and en\ndorsers who acclaim the merit of\nDoan\u2019s Ask your neighbor!\nDOAN\u2019S\nStimulant Diuretic to the Kidneys\nFoatcr-Milburn Co Mfg Chem Buffalo N Y\nTo The\nMothers\nOf Anderson Co\nThere are thorn who will say Hint\nsentiment ill business does not exist\nbut it is often quite hard for those\nmaking the charge to prove their elnitn\nThis institution utul its success owes\nu full fifty per cent to sentiment the\nsentiment of its patrons for the ins!\ntiition and tin Institution's sentiment\nfor is patrons built up ever a period\nof 42 years\nThen are mothers today in Ander\nson county who with their husband-\nnnd families have made this bank\ntlieir bank for years some since school\n(lays others us brides with husband\n(nine here to allow us to assist in tlieir\nsaving idans\nTo nil Mothers of the county we dedi\ncate ibis space It is tin Mother spirit\nwhich directs her children and chil\ndren's children to the paths of thrift\nmill comfort Wo extend nil goo I\nwishes\nMother\u2019 s Day\nMay 8\nLawrenceburg Nat\u2019l Bank\nEconomical Trrnntparlottam\n0W&\nCH4-1\nBeautiful Chevrolet\nJ\nL A\nX\nJever before\nSo many fme car features\nat such low prices\nOTOTOTOTOTOIOTO\nThe Most Beautiful Chev\nrolet embodies the largest\nnumber of fine car fea\ntures ever offered in alow\npriced automobile\nBodies by Fisher for ex\nample beaded paneled\nand finished in attractive\ncolors of genuine Duco\nsmartened by narrowed\nfront pillars upholstered\nin rich and durable fab\nrics completely appoint\ned and enhanced by\nsuch marks of distinction\nas full-crown one-piece\nfenders and bullet-type\nheadlamps\nAnd in addition the Most\nBeautiful Chevrolet pro\nvides many mechanical\nimprovements A new AC\noil filter and AC air clean\ner add to the performance\nand dependability of the\nChevrolet motor A hill\n17- inch steering wheel\ncoincidental steering and\nignition lock improved\ntransmission new gaso\nline gauge newtire carrier\nall of these are now\nstandard equipment or\nthe new Chevrolet\nCome to our salesroom\nand see the new car that is\nbreaking every precedent\nfor popularity Learn for\nyourself why it has every\nwhere been acclaimed as\nthe greatest automobile\nvalue of all time\nOH COACH-\n595\ncourt 625\nOk\nSEDAN\nQbSprt v\nCABRIOLET A 3\nLANDAU '745\nTOTS I NO ff ff\n4' SOAPS TVS 9 Ms 9\n495\niCImmtsOnl\nTRUCK '395\n(CUmkOut\nAll IVkss FOB FliocXkk\nBalloon lire standard\nequipment on all models\nCheck Chevrolet\nDelivered Prices\nThey include the lowest\nhandling nnd financing\ncharges available\nMOORE MOTOR SALES COMPANY\nAUTHORIZED CHEVROLET DEALERS\nLawrenceburg\nQUALITY AT\nKentucky\nLOW\nCOST","height":"26560","width":"17628"}}
